            <zone forceUpdate='true' h='19625' id='12' type-v2='text' w='98400' x='800' y='79375'>
              <formatted-text>
                <run bold='true' fontalignment='0'>Key Insights</run>
                <run fontalignment='0'>
• Employees working overtime demonstrate substantially higher attrition rates than those with standard work schedules. 
• Lower-income employee groups experience higher turnover rates, indicating compensation may influence employee retention.
• Attrition is highest among employees in their early years (0-2 years) with the organization, highlighting onboarding and early-tenure retention challenges.
• Lower job satisfaction levels are strongly associated with increased employee turnover risk.
</run>
                <run bold='true' fontalignment='0'>Recommendation</run>
                <run fontalignment='0'>
• Evaluate overtime practices and workload allocation within high-risk teams.
• Review compensation competitiveness for lower-income employee segments.
• Enhance onboarding, mentoring, and employee engagement initiatives during the first few years of employment. 
• Proactively track employee satisfaction metrics to identify retention risks before turnover occurs.</run>
              </formatted-text>
              <zone-style>
                <format attr='border-color' value='#000000' />
                <format attr='border-style' value='none' />
                <format attr='border-width' value='0' />
                <format attr='margin' value='4' />
